Author-Name: HAYNE E. LELAND 
Title: Financial Synergies and the Optimal Scope of the Firm: Implications for Mergers, Spinoffs, and Structured Finance 
Abstract:
 Multiple activities may be separated financially, allowing each to
 optimize its financial structure, or combined in a firm with a single
 optimal financial structure. We consider activities with nonsynergistic
 operational cash flows, and examine the purely financial benefits of
 separation versus merger. The magnitude of financial synergies depends
 upon tax rates, default costs, relative size, and the riskiness and
 correlation of cash flows. Contrary to accepted wisdom, financial
 synergies from mergers can be negative if firms have quite different risks
 or default costs. The results provide a rationale for structured finance
 techniques such as asset securitization and project finance. Copyright 2007 by The American Finance Association. 
