Author-Name: JARRAD HARFORD 
Author-Name: KAI LI 
Title: Decoupling CEO Wealth and Firm Performance: The Case of Acquiring CEOs 
Abstract:
 We explore how compensation policies following mergers affect a CEO's
 incentives to pursue a merger. We find that even in mergers where bidding
 shareholders are worse off, bidding CEOs are better off three quarters of
 the time. Following a merger, a CEO's pay and overall wealth become
 insensitive to negative stock performance, but a CEO's wealth rises in
 step with positive stock performance. Corporate governance matters;
 bidding firms with stronger boards retain the sensitivity of their CEOs'
 compensation to poor performance following the merger. In comparison, we
 find that CEOs are not rewarded for undertaking major capital
 expenditures. Copyright 2007 by The American Finance Association. 
